##New World Church in South Korea: An accomplice to the outbreak

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

The following article is from the international times and is written by the International Times

To provide professional analysis of international political events and trends, analyze China's position in a pluralistic world, release the enthusiasm and unlimited possibilities behind the "cold" international news.

Liu Dong, thepaper.cn

The New World Church is now at the heart of the new crown pneumonia epidemic in South Korea.

On March 2, Lee Man-Hee, an 88-year-old South Korean, fell to his knees in front of the national media, Kowtowing twice. "On behalf of the New World Church, I would like to extend my sincere apologies to the people. Although not intentionally, many people are still infected. We did everything we could, but we couldn't stop it. I seek the forgiveness of my people. I also seek the government's forgiveness."

It was the first time the church's top leader had spoken out in the two weeks since the outbreak in South Korea, and it brought the church back into the fold. Despite his apologies, Lee Man-Hee also dismissed accusations that the church was in trouble -- as if the church's actions had exacerbated the outbreak. This is clearly not to the satisfaction of the people. The press conference lasted only 20 minutes and ended abruptly after loud protests from the crowd and numerous questions from reporters.

If the watershed is the confirmation of a new coronavirus infection by a devotee of the Daegu branch of the new world on February 18th, Korea's epidemic prevention and control war can be divided into two distinct stories. South Korea had been one of the first countries in the world to detect imported cases. At one point, there was a 4-day increase in the number of cases. That all changed after Feb. 18, when case number 31 emerged and the epidemic took a turn for the worse. In just two weeks, South Korea has become the country with the worst outbreak outside of China.

As of March 4,5,328 confirmed cases had been reported in South Korea, of which 4,006 were in Taegu. The Xintiandi church-related cases were the largest group, with at least 2,418 cases, far outnumbering the rest of the population. At present, caught in the "bitter war" of the South Korean epidemic is still no sign of slowing down, the number of infections continue to increase.

The "super-spreading event" , which started in the Daegu branch of the New World Church, was the turning point of the Korean epidemic. Why has the new World Church, originally a victim of the outbreak, become the focus of public criticism in South Korea? Why does the government keep saying it's not cooperating with the investigation? What is the reason for some experts to worry that Xintiandi may become a further expansion of the epidemic "accomplice" ?

The New World Church outbreak is not a simple public health event. To answer these questions, we need to go deeper into the new world church. To this end, the paper (www.thepaper.cn ) conducted an exclusive interview with former members of the new World Church and interviewed religious experts, Korean cultural experts and legal experts, combining relevant public information from the Korean government and the New World Church, restore comb out the whole outbreak of the process of key details, to find Daegu epidemic behind the more complex truth.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Lee Man-Hee kowtowed at the press conference

Super-propagation event

In early 2014, a high school classmate introduced Zhang Fan, who was in graduate school at the time, to a class that described itself as a Bible study.

"after the first audition, I was impressed, " Zhang Fan told thepaper.cn, recalling the scene six years ago. "I thought the Bible was an important book for understanding the 'origins' of Western civilization (Greek and Hebrew) , and it would be nice to have a free opportunity to learn more about it, so I went on. "

More than two months later, the head of the class decided that Zhang Fan could "further his studies" and encouraged him to take the next stage, called the "Gospel Room. ". It was around this time that he began to understand that the group behind the workshop was actually an organization called the new heaven and Earth Church.

After the Gospel Room, Zhang Fan was asked to continue his studies at the new world seminary, which is divided into elementary, intermediate and advanced classes that take place two to three times a week for more than a year. In class, he was inculcated with a "new-world theology" that combined perversion of parts of the Bible with extreme hermeneutic and eschatological theories.

In retrospect, Zhang Fan says, the curriculum was "rigorous" . "If you follow their path, you will definitely be brought in, and all for the ultimate [ acceptance ] of Lee Man-Hee as the supreme authority. "

After graduation from the "seminary" , after rigorous written tests and interviews, Zhang Fan was finally eligible to officially join the church, was registered by the South Korean New World Church headquarters, become an official believer.

The organization was founded by Lee Man-Hee in 1984 and is known as the new heaven and Earth Evidence Tent Temple Church, according to the Church's official website. The group now has about 212,000 full members in South Korea, according to the group's first disclosure since the outbreak. Because of doctrinal problems and the worship of Lee Man-Hee himself, the new Heaven Church was widely regarded as "heresy" or "heresy" by the mainstream Korean church shortly after its birth. The group has also long been notorious in South Korea for scandals such as membership fraud and defrauding believers of their money.

In mid-january, thousands of core members from all over the world gathered at Sundance headquarters in Kwach'ǒn 见 Gwacheon, near Seoul, South Korea, for one of the organization's most important annual events, the "International Congress" .

Notably, South Korea's deputy minister of Central anti-epidemic strategy, Kwon jun-yu, said at a press conference on March 3 that two South Korean Shintiandi devotees visited Wuhan in January this year, one of them was confirmed to have contracted the new coronavirus in late February. However, it is not yet possible to determine whether this patient is related to the collective infection that triggered the new world church.

It has been difficult to determine clearly how the Daegu outbreak first spread and how it was "patient zero, " but events during this period can provide important clues for retracing the outbreak.

According to an investigation by the South Korean Department of Disease Control and Prevention, shortly after the above-mentioned "international conference" of Xintiandi in mid-january, an unknown number of members of Xintiandi between January 31 and February 2, came to Lee Man-Hee's hometown, North Gyeongsang Province, to attend the funeral of Lee Man-Hee's 92 year old brother at the local Nant-le-grand Hospital. Including 47 Xintiandi members from Taegu.

In mid-february, inpatients and medical staff in the closed psychiatric ward of Dannan hospital began to develop symptoms of fever. On 18 February, two people were diagnosed in the hospital. Since then, the hospital has seen an explosive increase in confirmed cases and is now the second-largest affected area in South Korea after Taegu.

At the same time, not far from the Qingdaojun city of Daegu, a "epidemic storm" is quietly brewing.

Daegu, a 62-year-old woman who was later confirmed as case No. 31 by South Korea's disease control and prevention authorities, first went to a small local hospital on February 7 to complain of a sore throat. On February 9, she attended a service attended by 1,000 people from the new World Church in Daegu.

The next day, she had a persistent fever. The doctor admitted her for treatment. On February 16, she left the hospital and went to church again.

Health officials said doctors had advised the woman on at least two occasions to transfer to a larger hospital for a new coronavirus test, but she refused. She insisted that she had not been to China in recent months, nor had she come into contact with anyone infected. At present, South Korea's disease control authorities are still trying to figure out how she was infected.

On February 18, case No. 31 was confirmed, but the virus had already spread within the new World Church in Taegu. Located in a nine-storey tower in downtown Taegu, the church is one of Shintiandi's most active branches in South Korea, with an estimated 10,000 followers.

In a confined space in winter, thousands of people sing, talk and get up close and personal for hours, all of which make perfect conditions for the virus to spread. Over the next few days, new believers were diagnosed. As of March 3, as many as 62 per cent of the 4,328 Xintiandi devotees tested in Taegu were positive, far higher than the rest of the population.

The outbreak began in Daegu city, where the virus spread through the streets of Taegu, breaking what appeared to be a tight quarantine net in an instant. Then came the South Korean epidemic prevention and control of the overall situation of a sharp decline.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
People wearing masks on the streets of Korea

Refused to cooperate with the government investigation

Having confirmed case No. 31's connection to the church in Daegu Xintiandi, the Korean authorities quickly approached the church in the hope that they could assist in providing a list of church members to track down thousands of participants and their close contacts, to prevent the outbreak from spreading. It took a week, however, for the Church to "reluctantly" provide the authorities with an incomplete list of its members.

According to the South Korean Disease Control Department disclosed that the initial investigation, the 31st case is also refused to cooperate, unwilling to reveal their whereabouts. It wasn't until authorities checked her cell phone records that she visited Cheongdo County in early February. The patient claimed, however, that she had not been to Dannan hospital or to a funeral, but had used a local public bath while clearing the road.

Even more inexplicably, after case number 31 was confirmed, the new World Church in Taegu sent a message to its members to continue their activities and told them that if they were asked by government officials, they should deny their membership or attend church services. Several people close to the church confirmed the authenticity of the information to thepaper.cn.

"This behavior is not surprising to anyone familiar with the inner workings of Xintiandi, " Zhang Fan told The Paper news, "If I were a sick believer, my first reaction would be to report to my superiors, to follow the Church's guidance and arrangements, and never to listen to anyone, including my parents and officials. Because the most important thing is to keep the church safe."

The church later issued a statement saying that the individual's message did not represent its official policy and that disciplinary action had been taken against the individual who sent it.

Wan Yanjiao, a law doctor at Kyung Hee University in South Korea, believes that a series of anomalies in the early days of the new World Church were an important "accomplice" to the rapid spread and even runaway of the epidemic in Taegu.

"Xintiandi did not at first realize the seriousness of the outbreak or the danger it would cause to believers and the public, and has refused to cooperate with the government. It was not until Feb. 23, when the outbreak in Taegu was so severe that President Moon jae-in raised the alert to the highest level that the government had a basis to compel Xintiandi to cooperate that they reluctantly handed over the materials,"she said.

On February 24, Gyeonggi Province chief executive Lee Jae-Myung told TBS television that the new World Church did not initially cooperate with the South Korean government as promised. According to their information, only 100 of the group's 239 branches in Gyeonggi Province have real addresses.

In response, Zhang Fan explains, Xintiandi places its own secrecy and security above all else. He has seen first hand how the church's top brass have instructed them to empty their phones of all new world related information, and how to concoct excuses to deceive government officials and even their loved ones.

"They see themselves as a church with a single truth and can not be led around by others and stuck to their own set of rules. At the same time, they are constantly asking believers to lie and teaching us how to deceive those closest to us, including partners and children, without letting them know that they are believers in the new world,"Zhang Fan said.

In an internal letter to believers after the outbreak, Lee Man-Hee said, "the outbreak of this disease is the work of the devil to prevent the rapid growth of the new world. ". He himself refused to be tested by the health authorities until 29 February, before a press conference.

As the outbreak escalated, on Feb. 26, Lee Man-Hee had to publish a statement on the official Xintiandi website saying the group had been "actively cooperating with the South Korean government to prevent further spread of the virus. " And has handed over a list of all members of the congregation while the government protects private information.

But that hasn't made it any easier for the government to investigate and contact members of Xintiandi. On the same day, the new Gyeonggi Province government said it had to ask 210 Xintiandi members to call 33,000 other members because they do not usually take calls from non-members, according to the New York Times, asking if there were any symptoms.

In Taegu, police deployed 600 officers to knock on doors to find members of the list who had not been contacted and asked them to isolate themselves after they had not answered their phones or returned messages. Some church members were uncooperative, and police had to track cell phone calls and check surveillance footage to find them.

On February 28th Kwon young-jin, the mayor of Taegu, said the government had found that Shintiandi had deleted 1,762 members from its list, some of whom had been infected with the new coronavirus. He railed that Xintiandi was submitting "false information and obstructing the government's work" and would report the group to the police as "obstructing the government's efforts to contain the virus" .

The South Korean government believes that Xintiandi's actions have interfered with the government's efforts to deal with the epidemic, leading to an increase in the number of deaths. On March 1st Seoul's Mayor, Park Won-soon, went viral on social media, reporting that Lee Man-Hee and the head of the new World Church were responsible for the outbreak. The city of Seoul demanded that Shintiandi organizers provide full information about the believers and ordered them to be tested. If Lee Man-Hee fails to do so, leaders such as Lee Man-Hee will be charged with "manslaughter" .

The next day, Xintiandi hastily announced a press conference. At the meeting, Lee Man-Hee staged the "apology" at the beginning of this article.

In the eyes of Zhang Zhihua, a Chinese lawyer in South Korea, the press conference was simply Xintiandi's response to the pressure of prosecution to clear its name. In his press conference, Lee Man-Hee has also been passing the buck to the government.

"The South Korean Constitution guarantees the freedom of belief in Xintiandi to allow such an organization to exist. So as the leader should have a greater responsibility to make a correct judgment? If a lot of believers and innocent people get hurt because you didn't make the right call. Are you going to take the responsibility?"Zhang told thepaper.cn.

So what kind of organization is the new World Church in the eye of the Korean epidemic? What is it that makes Xintiandi believers so afraid to reveal their identity? Even at the cost of your own life?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At the new world headquarters

What kind of organization is New World Church

"I don't believe Xintiandi will come clean to the government because it will affect their interests and security and expose their secret missionary activities, " Yang Zicong, director-general of the Hong kong-based Concern Group on Newly Emerged Religions, told the paper.

Yang Zicong, who has long followed Xintiandi, said Xintiandi's response to the outbreak was in line with their usual attitude. "ultimately, because they have an anti-social mentality and are extremely self-centred, it is natural for them to be uncooperative. "

In South Korea, in recent decades there has been a proliferation of new religious organisations in the name of Christianity, often more attractive than the formal church. According to Yang, there are more than 100 such organizations in South Korea. These groups tend to place particular emphasis on eschatological pathos and the "Patriarch" concept.

"Korean folk culture is relatively simple, the nation itself has a more intense emotion, when introducing some religious culture from abroad, often branded 'Korean characteristics' , Christianity is no exception. Some folk religions, such as Shamanism, often show their marks when they develop,"Yang said.

This is evident in Xintiandi. According to the doctrine of the new world, Lee Man-Hee was God's last "prophet and promise" on Earth, receiving worshipers close to God. "This kind of spiritual manipulation is very strong, and Lee Man-Hee's influence within the church is unimaginable, " Zhang Fan said. "compared to the government, believers will choose to obey his commands unconditionally. ".

Lee Man-Hee was born in September 1931 in Qingdaojun, North Gyeongsang Province, and lived with Seoul's brother in the construction industry at the age of 17. He was baptized at the controversial Tabernacle templar church in South Korea. He later broke away from the church, calling himself the biblical "Shepherd of God's promises" and Lord of the second coming of Jesus, who founded the Church of new heaven and earth in 1984. The New World Church has its own calendar, with 1984 as the first year. It held its own "Olympics" , and the stadium was packed with worshippers from all over the world. Lee Man-Hee often wore Snow White, carried his trademark folding fan in his hand, and liked to salute his admirers.

From the start, Shintiandi was identified as "heresy" by the mainstream Korean Church (a religious sect that is at odds with Theology Orthodoxy) . The mainstream Korean church investigated and pointed out that Lee Man-Hee himself had no formal theological training and that his experience in the Tabernacle Church was a major source of his theological thinking. He did not recognize the Bible as the supreme authority of Faith, which is widely believed in Christianity. And those who claim to receive their revelation directly from God, only their own words are true.

Compared with other "heretical" churches, Xintiandi is the most hidden one, Yang said. A senior South Korean religious figure told The Paper that Shintiandi had been kept completely secret from the outside world because it was the first time outsiders knew how many people were in Shintiandi and where the facilities were located.

The New World Church is most criticized by the mainstream church for the way it recruits its followers. The above religious circles told thepaper.cn that if any heretical group was the most disruptive to the South Korean church, it would be Xintiandi. The New World Church often allows believers known as "reapers" to hide their true identity, infiltrate other churches, preach to Christians and drag them into the new world.

This is the most important reason why the church has been reluctant to cooperate with the authorities in making public its membership list. "All churches don't welcome people from the new world, and if their identities were made public, it would have a very negative impact, " Zhang Fan said. The South Korean government has also repeatedly found in the investigation, more than patients until their own diagnosis before revealing that they are believers in Xintiandi. Among them was a government official in Daegu who was responsible for testing for the new coronavirus and did not admit to being a member of the new World Church until he tested positive.

But Kim Shin-chang, head of the mission department at Xintiandi International, argued in an interview with the CNN that followers of Xintiandi were discriminated against because they were deemed heretical, that's why many church members are afraid to reveal their identities.

Huang Yong Yong, assistant professor of Korean at the National Sun Yat-sen University, said: "There are problems with the authenticity of the lists submitted by the new heaven and Earth Church and many secret missionary and gathering facilities have not yet been made public, which has caused interference in the authorities' anti-epidemic investigation. What's more, although the new World Church has stopped large-scale services, small-scale Gatherings and Missionary Activities in Gospel rooms masquerading as cafes and other facilities are likely to continue, which is very dangerous."

More importantly, Huang always said that any religion using religious authority to control believers physically and mentally, and thus disrupt the normal social order, is definitely harmful.

But he also believes that, despite the church's apparent culpability in dealing with the outbreak, it can not take all the blame and blame just because it was the epicenter of the outbreak.

Since the outbreak, more than 500,000 people have signed an online petition to the South Korean President's office demanding the dissolution of the new World Church.

In 2017, in contact with another "heretic" church, Zhang Fan realised that his new world church might also be "problematic" . "then I went online and looked up a lot of information, found a lot of negative content, and basically decided it was a cult. After a lot of thinking, I decided to quit, " Zhang Fan said, after leaving Xintiandi, the organization's regional director personally came to talk to him and sent his high school classmates to persuade him to come back. Finally, as a friend, Zhang Fan reluctantly agreed. Soon after, however, Xintiandi took it upon itself to remove him after he published material that "tarnished the image of the patriarch. ".

In Zhang Fan's view, Lee Man-Hee's apology at the press conference was superficial and evaded the core issues of the new World Church, and it in no way implied that he would cooperate with the government. "Just because he doesn't want to be prosecuted, he doesn't want to go to jail, not even for a day. "

"This is a 'cult' that controls people, " Zhang Fan concluded. "If they want to cooperate with the government, they have to give up their own ways. That's something they would never do. ".

Zhang Fan was given an alias at the request of the interviewee
